# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: gradient-descent-algo
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] In machine learning, **backpropagation** is a gradient computation method commonly used for training a neural network in computing parameter updates.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] It is an efficient application of the chain rule to neural networks.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] Backpropagation efficiently computes the gradient of the loss with respect to the network weights for a single input–output example.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] It does this by propagating derivatives backward, one layer at a time, from the output layer to the input layer, thereby avoiding redundant chain-rule calculations.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] Strictly speaking, the term *backpropagation* refers only to an algorithm for efficiently computing the gradient, not how the gradient is used, but the term is often used loosely to refer to the entire learning algorithm.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] This includes changing model parameters in the negative direction of the gradient, such as by stochastic gradient descent, or as an intermediate step in a more complicated optimizer, such as Adaptive Moment Estimation.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] Backpropagation had multiple discoveries and partial discoveries, with a tangled history and terminology (see § History).
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] Some other names for the technique include "reverse mode of automatic differentiation" or "reverse accumulation".
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] Backpropagation computes the gradient in weight space of a feedforward neural network, with respect to a loss function.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] In the derivation of backpropagation, other intermediate quantities are used by introducing them as needed below.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] Bias terms are not treated specially since they correspond to a weight with a fixed input of 1.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] For backpropagation the specific loss function and activation functions do not matter as long as they and their derivatives can be evaluated efficiently.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] Traditional activation functions include sigmoid, tanh, ReLU, Swish, Mish, and many others.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] For a training set there will be a set of input–output pairs, $\left\{(x_{i},y_{i})\right\}$ .
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] Note the distinction: during model evaluation the weights are fixed while the inputs vary (and the target output may be unknown), and the network ends with the output layer (it does not include the loss function).
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] During model training the input–output pair is fixed while the weights vary, and the network ends with the loss function.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] Backpropagation computes the gradient for a *fixed* input–output pair $(x_{i},y_{i})$ , where the weights $w_{jk}^{l}$ can vary.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] Each individual component of the gradient, $\partial C/\partial w_{jk}^{l},$ can be computed by the chain rule; but doing this separately for each weight is inefficient.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] Backpropagation efficiently computes the gradient by avoiding duplicate calculations and not computing unnecessary intermediate values, by computing the gradient of each layer – specifically the gradient of the weighted *input* of each layer, denoted by $\delta ^{l}$ – from back to front.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] First, it avoids duplication because when computing the gradient at layer l , it is unnecessary to recompute all derivatives on later layers $l+1,l+2,\ldots$ each time.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] Backpropagation can be expressed for simple feedforward networks in terms of matrix multiplication, or more generally in terms of the adjoint graph.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] To compute this, one starts with the input x and works forward; denote the weighted input of each hidden layer as $z^{l}$ and the output of hidden layer l as the activation $a^{l}$ .
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] For backpropagation, the activation $a^{l}$ as well as the derivatives $(f^{l})'$ (evaluated at $z^{l}$ ) must be cached for use during the backwards pass.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] Note that $\delta ^{l}$ is a vector, of length equal to the number of nodes in level l ; each component is interpreted as the "cost attributable to (the value of) that node".
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] The factor of $a^{l-1}$ is because the weights $W^{l}$ between level $l-1$ and l affect level l proportionally to the inputs (activations): the inputs are fixed, the weights vary.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] The gradients of the weights can thus be computed using a few matrix multiplications for each level; this is backpropagation.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] Multiplying starting from $\nabla _{a^{L}}C$ – propagating the error *backwards* – means that each step simply multiplies a vector ( $\delta ^{l}$ ) by the matrices of weights $(W^{l})^{T}$ and derivatives of activations $(f^{l-1})'$ .
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] By contrast, multiplying forwards, starting from the changes at an earlier layer, means that each multiplication multiplies a *matrix* by a *matrix*.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] For more general graphs, and other advanced variations, backpropagation can be understood in terms of automatic differentiation, where backpropagation is a special case of reverse accumulation (or "reverse mode").
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] The goal of any supervised learning algorithm is to find a function that best maps a set of inputs to their correct output.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] The motivation for backpropagation is to train a multi-layered neural network such that it can learn the appropriate internal representations to allow it to learn any arbitrary mapping of input to output.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] To understand the mathematical derivation of the backpropagation algorithm, it helps to first develop some intuition about the relationship between the actual output of a neuron and the correct output for a particular training example.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] Consider a simple neural network with two input units, one output unit and no hidden units, and in which each neuron uses a linear output (unlike most work on neural networks, in which mapping from inputs to outputs is non-linear) that is the weighted sum of its input.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] Initially, before training, the weights will be set randomly.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] Then the neuron learns from training examples, which in this case consist of a set of tuples $(x_{1},x_{2},t)$ where $x_{1}$ and $x_{2}$ are the inputs to the network and t is the correct output (the output the network should produce given those inputs, when it has been trained).
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] The initial network, given $x_{1}$ and $x_{2}$ , will compute an output y that likely differs from t (given random weights).
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] A loss function $L(t,y)$ is used for measuring the discrepancy between the target output t and the computed output y.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] For regression analysis problems the squared error can be used as a loss function, for classification the categorical cross-entropy can be used.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] Consider the network on a single training case: $(1,1,0)$ .
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] Thus, the input $x_{1}$ and $x_{2}$ are 1 and 1 respectively and the correct output, t is 0.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] Now if the relation is plotted between the network's output y on the horizontal axis and the error E on the vertical axis, the result is a parabola.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] The minimum of the parabola corresponds to the output y which minimizes the error E.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] For a single training case, the minimum also touches the horizontal axis, which means the error will be zero and the network can produce an output y that exactly matches the target output t.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] Therefore, the problem of mapping inputs to outputs can be reduced to an optimization problem of finding a function that will produce the minimal error.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] where $w_{1}$ and $w_{2}$ are the weights on the connection from the input units to the output unit.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] Therefore, the error also depends on the incoming weights to the neuron, which is ultimately what needs to be changed in the network to enable learning.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] Then, the loss function E takes the form of a parabolic cylinder with its base directed along $w_{1}=-w_{2}$ .
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] Since all sets of weights that satisfy $w_{1}=-w_{2}$ minimize the loss function, in this case additional constraints are required to converge to a unique solution.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] Additional constraints could either be generated by setting specific conditions to the weights, or by injecting additional training data.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] One commonly used algorithm to find the set of weights that minimizes the error is gradient descent.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] By backpropagation, the steepest descent direction is calculated of the loss function versus the present synaptic weights.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] Then, the weights can be modified along the steepest descent direction, and the error is minimized in an efficient way.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] The gradient descent method involves calculating the derivative of the loss function with respect to the weights of the network.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] This is normally done using backpropagation.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] is the actual output of the output neuron.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] In this section, the order of the weight indexes are reversed relative to the prior section: $w_{ij}$ is weight from the i th to the j th unit.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] where the activation function $\varphi$ is non-linear and differentiable over the activation region (the ReLU is not differentiable at one point).
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] The input ${\text{net}}_{j}$ to a neuron is the weighted sum of outputs $o_{k}$ of previous neurons.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] If the neuron is in the first layer after the input layer, the $o_{k}$ of the input layer are simply the inputs $x_{k}$ to the network.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] The number of input units to the neuron is n .
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] The variable $w_{kj}$ denotes the weight between neuron k of the previous layer and neuron j of the current layer.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] If the neuron is in the first layer after the input layer, $o_{i}$ is just $x_{i}$ .
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] This is the reason why backpropagation requires that the activation function be differentiable.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] However, if j is in an arbitrary inner layer of the network, finding the derivative E with respect to $o_{j}$ is less obvious.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] To update the weight $w_{ij}$ using gradient descent, one must choose a learning rate, $\eta >0$ .
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] The change in weight needs to reflect the impact on E of an increase or decrease in $w_{ij}$ .
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] If ${\frac {\partial E}{\partial w_{ij}}}>0$ , an increase in $w_{ij}$ increases E ; conversely, if ${\frac {\partial E}{\partial w_{ij}}}<0$ , an increase in $w_{ij}$ decreases E .
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] The new $\Delta w_{ij}$ is added to the old weight, and the product of the learning rate and the gradient, multiplied by $-1$ guarantees that $w_{ij}$ changes in a way that always decreases E .
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] Using a Hessian matrix of second-order derivatives of the error function, the Levenberg–Marquardt algorithm often converges faster than first-order gradient descent, especially when the topology of the error function is complicated.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] It may also find solutions in smaller node counts for which other methods might not converge.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] The Hessian can be approximated by the Fisher information matrix.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] As an example, consider a simple feedforward network.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] Arbitrary-order derivatives in arbitrary computational graphs can be computed with backpropagation, but with more complex expressions for higher orders.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] The loss function is a function that maps values of one or more variables onto a real number intuitively representing some "cost" associated with those values.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] For backpropagation, the loss function calculates the difference between the network output and its expected output, after a training example has propagated through the network.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] The mathematical expression of the loss function must fulfill two conditions in order for it to be possibly used in backpropagation.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] The first is that it can be written as an average ${\textstyle E={\frac {1}{n}}\sum _{x}E_{x}}$ over error functions ${\textstyle E_{x}}$ , for ${\textstyle n}$ individual training examples, ${\textstyle x}$ .
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] The reason for this assumption is that the backpropagation algorithm calculates the gradient of the error function for a single training example, which needs to be generalized to the overall error function.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] The second assumption is that it can be written as a function of the outputs from the neural network.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] Select an error function $E(y,y')$ measuring the difference between two outputs.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] Backpropagation had been derived repeatedly, as it is essentially an efficient application of the chain rule (first written down by Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz in 1676) to neural networks.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] The terminology "back-propagating error correction" was introduced in 1962 by Frank Rosenblatt, but he did not know how to implement this.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] In any case, he only studied neurons whose outputs were discrete levels, which only had zero derivatives, making backpropagation impossible.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] Precursors to backpropagation appeared in optimal control theory since 1950s.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] Yann LeCun et al credits 1950s work by Pontryagin and others in optimal control theory, especially the adjoint state method, for being a continuous-time version of backpropagation.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] Hecht-Nielsen credits the Robbins–Monro algorithm (1951) and Arthur Bryson and Yu-Chi Ho's *Applied Optimal Control* (1969) as presages of backpropagation.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] In 1962, Stuart Dreyfus published a simpler derivation based only on the chain rule.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] In 1973, he adapted parameters of controllers in proportion to error gradients.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] Unlike modern backpropagation, these precursors used standard Jacobian matrix calculations from one stage to the previous one, neither addressing direct links across several stages nor potential additional efficiency gains due to network sparsity.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] The ADALINE (1960) learning algorithm was gradient descent with a squared error loss for a single layer.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] The first multilayer perceptron (MLP) with more than one layer trained by stochastic gradient descent was published in 1967 by Shun'ichi Amari.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] The MLP had 5 layers, with 2 learnable layers, and it learned to classify patterns not linearly separable.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] Modern backpropagation was first published by Seppo Linnainmaa as "reverse mode of automatic differentiation" (1970) for discrete connected networks of nested differentiable functions.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] In 1982, Paul Werbos applied backpropagation to MLPs in the way that has become standard.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] Werbos described how he developed backpropagation in an interview.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] In 1971, during his PhD work, he developed backpropagation to mathematicize Freud's "flow of psychic energy".
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] He faced repeated difficulty in publishing the work, only managing in 1981.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] He also claimed that "the first practical application of back-propagation was for estimating a dynamic model to predict nationalism and social communications in 1974" by him.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] Rumelhart independently developed backpropagation and taught the algorithm to others in his research circle.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] He did not cite previous work as he was unaware of them.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] He published the algorithm first in a 1985 paper, then in a 1986 *Nature* paper an experimental analysis of the technique.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] These papers became highly cited, contributed to the popularization of backpropagation, and coincided with the resurging research interest in neural networks during the 1980s.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] In 1985, the method was also described by David Parker.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] Yann LeCun proposed an alternative form of backpropagation for neural networks in his PhD thesis in 1987.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] Gradient descent took a considerable amount of time to reach acceptance.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] Some early objections were: there were no guarantees that gradient descent could reach a global minimum, only local minimum; neurons were "known" by physiologists as making discrete signals (0/1), not continuous ones, and with discrete signals, there is no gradient to take.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] See the interview with Geoffrey Hinton, who was awarded the 2024 Nobel Prize in Physics for his contributions to the field.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] Contributing to the acceptance were several applications in training neural networks via backpropagation, sometimes achieving popularity outside the research circles.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] In 1987, NETtalk learned to convert English text into pronunciation.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] Sejnowski tried training it with both backpropagation and Boltzmann machine, but found the backpropagation significantly faster, so he used it for the final NETtalk.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] The NETtalk program became a popular success, appearing on the *Today* show.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] Pomerleau published ALVINN, a neural network trained to drive autonomously using backpropagation.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] The LeNet was published in 1989 to recognize handwritten zip codes.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] In 1992, TD-Gammon achieved top human level play in backgammon.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] It was a reinforcement learning agent with a neural network with two layers, trained by backpropagation.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] In 1993, Eric Wan won an international pattern recognition contest through backpropagation.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] During the 2000s it fell out of favour, but returned in the 2010s, benefiting from cheap, powerful GPU-based computing systems.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] Error backpropagation has been suggested to explain human brain event-related potential (ERP) components like the N400 and P600.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/backpropagation] In 2023, a backpropagation algorithm was implemented on a photonic processor by a team at Stanford University.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/convex-optimization] The feasible set C of the optimization problem consists of all points $\mathbf {x} \in {\mathcal {D}}$ satisfying the inequality and the equality constraints.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/convex-optimization] This set is convex because ${\mathcal {D}}$ is convex, the sublevel sets of convex functions are convex, affine sets are convex, and the intersection of convex sets is convex.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/convex-optimization] Many optimization problems can be equivalently formulated in this standard form.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/convex-optimization] For example, the problem of maximizing a concave function f can be re-formulated equivalently as the problem of minimizing the convex function $-f$ .
[src:gradient-descent-algo/convex-optimization] The problem of maximizing a concave function over a convex set is commonly called a convex optimization problem.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/convex-optimization] In the standard form it is possible to assume, without loss of generality, that the objective function *f* is a linear function.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/convex-optimization] where K is a closed pointed convex cone, L is a linear subspace of R*n*, and b is a vector in R*n*.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/convex-optimization] A linear program in standard form is the special case in which K is the nonnegative orthant of R*n*.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/convex-optimization] It is possible to convert a convex program in standard form, to a convex program with no equality constraints.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/convex-optimization] Denote the equality constraints *hi*(*x*)=0 as *Ax*=*b*, where *A* has *n* columns.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/convex-optimization] If *Ax*=*b* is infeasible, then of course the original problem is infeasible.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/convex-optimization] Otherwise, it has some solution *x*0 , and the set of all solutions can be presented as: *Fz*+*x*0, where *z* is in *Rk*, *k*=*n*-rank(*A*), and *F* is an *n*-by-*k* matrix.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/convex-optimization] Note that there are rank(*A*) fewer variables.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/convex-optimization] This means that, in principle, one can restrict attention to convex optimization problems without equality constraints.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/convex-optimization] In practice, however, it is often preferred to retain the equality constraints, since they might make some algorithms more efficient, and also make the problem easier to understand and analyze.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/convex-optimization] These results are used by the theory of convex minimization along with geometric notions from functional analysis (in Hilbert spaces) such as the Hilbert projection theorem, the separating hyperplane theorem, and Farkas' lemma.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/convex-optimization] The convex programs easiest to solve are the *unconstrained* problems, or the problems with only equality constraints.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/convex-optimization] As the equality constraints are all linear, they can be eliminated with linear algebra and integrated into the objective, thus converting an equality-constrained problem into an unconstrained one.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/convex-optimization] In the class of unconstrained (or equality-constrained) problems, the simplest ones are those in which the objective is quadratic.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/convex-optimization] For these problems, the KKT conditions (which are necessary for optimality) are all linear, so they can be solved analytically.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/convex-optimization] For unconstrained (or equality-constrained) problems with a general convex objective that is twice-differentiable, Newton's method can be used.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/convex-optimization] It can be seen as reducing a general unconstrained convex problem, to a sequence of quadratic problems.Newton's method can be combined with line search for an appropriate step size, and it can be mathematically proven to converge quickly.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/convex-optimization] Other efficient algorithms for unconstrained minimization are gradient descent (a special case of steepest descent).
[src:gradient-descent-algo/convex-optimization] The more challenging problems are those with inequality constraints.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/convex-optimization] A common way to solve them is to reduce them to unconstrained problems by adding a barrier function, enforcing the inequality constraints, to the objective function.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/convex-optimization] Such methods are called interior point methods.They have to be initialized by finding a feasible interior point using by so-called *phase I* methods, which either find a feasible point or show that none exist.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/convex-optimization] Phase I methods generally consist of reducing the search in question to a simpler convex optimization problem.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/convex-optimization] Subgradient methods can be implemented simply and so are widely used.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/convex-optimization] Dual subgradient methods are subgradient methods applied to a dual problem.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/convex-optimization] The drift-plus-penalty method is similar to the dual subgradient method, but takes a time average of the primal variables.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/convex-optimization] Consider a convex minimization problem given in standard form by a cost function $f(x)$ and inequality constraints $g_{i}(x)\leq 0$ for $1\leq i\leq m$ .
[src:gradient-descent-algo/convex-optimization] then the statement above can be strengthened to require that $\lambda _{0}=1$ .
[src:gradient-descent-algo/convex-optimization] Conversely, if some x in X satisfies (1)–(3) for scalars $\lambda _{0},\ldots ,\lambda _{m}$ with $\lambda _{0}=1$ then x is certain to minimize f over X .
[src:gradient-descent-algo/convex-optimization] There is a large software ecosystem for convex optimization.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/convex-optimization] This ecosystem has two main categories: *solvers* on the one hand and *modeling tools* (or *interfaces*) on the other hand.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/convex-optimization] Solvers implement the algorithms themselves and are usually written in C.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/convex-optimization] They require users to specify optimization problems in very specific formats which may not be natural from a modeling perspective.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/convex-optimization] Modeling tools are separate pieces of software that let the user specify an optimization in higher-level syntax.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/convex-optimization] They manage all transformations to and from the user's high-level model and the solver's input/output format.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/convex-optimization] The first shows modelling tools (such as CVXPY and JuMP.jl) and the second shows solvers (such as SCS and MOSEK).
[src:gradient-descent-algo/convex-optimization] Extensions of convex optimization include the optimization of biconvex, pseudo-convex, and quasiconvex functions.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/convex-optimization] Extensions of the theory of convex analysis and iterative methods for approximately solving non-convex minimization problems occur in the field of generalized convexity, also known as abstract convex analysis.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] The idea is to take repeated steps in the opposite direction of the gradient (or approximate gradient) of the function at the current point, because this is the direction of steepest descent.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] Conversely, stepping in the direction of the gradient will lead to a trajectory that maximizes that function; the procedure is then known as *gradient ascent*.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] Gradient descent should not be confused with local search algorithms, although both are iterative methods for optimization.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] Gradient descent is particularly useful in machine learning and artificial intelligence for minimizing the cost or loss function.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] Gradient descent is generally attributed to Augustin-Louis Cauchy, who first suggested it in 1847.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] Jacques Hadamard independently proposed a similar method in 1907.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] Its convergence properties for non-linear optimization problems were first studied by Haskell Curry in 1944, with the method becoming increasingly well-studied and used in the following decades.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] A simple extension of gradient descent, stochastic gradient descent, serves as the most basic algorithm used for training most deep networks today.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] for a small enough step size or learning rate $\eta \in \mathbb {R} _{+}$ , then $f(\mathbf {a_{n}} )\geq f(\mathbf {a_{n+1}} )$ .
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] In other words, the term $\eta \nabla f(\mathbf {a} )$ is subtracted from $\mathbf {a}$ because we want to move against the gradient, toward the local minimum.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] so the sequence $(\mathbf {x} _{n})$ converges to the desired local minimum.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] Note that the value of the *step size* $\eta$ is allowed to change at every iteration.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] It is possible to guarantee the convergence to a local minimum under certain assumptions on the function f (for example, f convex and $\nabla f$ Lipschitz) and particular choices of $\eta$ .
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] as in the Barzilai-Borwein method, or a sequence $\eta _{n}$ satisfying the Wolfe conditions (which can be found by using line search).
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] When the function f is convex, all local minima are also global minima, so in this case gradient descent can converge to the global solution.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] This process is illustrated in the adjacent picture.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] Here, f is assumed to be defined on the plane, and that its graph has a bowl shape.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] The blue curves are the contour lines, that is, the regions on which the value of f is constant.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] A red arrow originating at a point shows the direction of the negative gradient at that point.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] Note that the (negative) gradient at a point is orthogonal to the contour line going through that point.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] We see that gradient *descent* leads us to the bottom of the bowl, that is, to the point where the value of the function f is minimal.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] The basic intuition behind gradient descent can be illustrated by a hypothetical scenario.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] People are stuck in the mountains and are trying to get down (i.e., trying to find the global minimum).
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] There is heavy fog such that visibility is extremely low.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] Therefore, the path down the mountain is not visible, so they must use local information to find the minimum.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] They can use the method of gradient descent, which involves looking at the steepness of the hill at their current position, then proceeding in the direction with the steepest descent (i.e., downhill).
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] If they were trying to find the top of the mountain (i.e., the maximum), then they would proceed in the direction of steepest ascent (i.e., uphill).
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] Using this method, they would eventually find their way down the mountain or possibly get stuck in some hole (i.e., local minimum or saddle point), like a mountain lake.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] However, assume also that the steepness of the hill is not immediately obvious with simple observation, but rather it requires a sophisticated instrument to measure, which the people happen to have at that moment.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] It takes quite some time to measure the steepness of the hill with the instrument.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] Thus, they should minimize their use of the instrument if they want to get down the mountain before sunset.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] The difficulty then is choosing the frequency at which they should measure the steepness of the hill so as not to go off track.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] In this analogy, the people represent the algorithm, and the path taken down the mountain represents the sequence of parameter settings that the algorithm will explore.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] The steepness of the hill represents the slope of the function at that point.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] The instrument used to measure steepness is differentiation.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] The direction they choose to travel in aligns with the gradient of the function at that point.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] The amount of time they travel before taking another measurement is the step size.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] Since using a step size $\eta$ that is too small would slow convergence, and a $\eta$ too large would lead to overshoot and divergence, finding a good setting of $\eta$ is an important practical problem.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] Philip Wolfe also advocated using "clever choices of the [descent] direction" in practice.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] While using a direction that deviates from the steepest descent direction may seem counter-intuitive, the idea is that the smaller slope may be compensated for by being sustained over a much longer distance.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] Finding good settings of $\mathbf {p} _{n}$ and $\eta _{n}$ requires some thought.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] First of all, we would like the update direction to point downhill.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] Mathematically, letting $\theta _{n}$ denote the angle between $-\nabla f(\mathbf {a_{n}} )$ and $\mathbf {p} _{n}$ , this requires that $\cos \theta _{n}>0.$ To say more, we need more information about the objective function that we are optimising.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] This inequality implies that the amount by which we can be sure the function f is decreased depends on a trade off between the two terms in square brackets.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] The first term in square brackets measures the angle between the descent direction and the negative gradient.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] The second term measures how quickly the gradient changes along the descent direction.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] In principle inequality (**1**) could be optimized over $\mathbf {p} _{n}$ and $\eta _{n}$ to choose an optimal step size and direction.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] The problem is that evaluating the second term in square brackets requires evaluating $\nabla f(\mathbf {a} _{n}-t\eta _{n}\mathbf {p} _{n})$ , and extra gradient evaluations are generally expensive and undesirable.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] Usually by following one of the recipes above, convergence to a local minimum can be guaranteed.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] reformulated as a quadratic minimization problem.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] The line search minimization, finding the locally optimal step size $\eta$ on every iteration, can be performed analytically for quadratic functions, and explicit formulas for the locally optimal $\eta$ are known.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] The method is rarely used for solving linear equations, with the conjugate gradient method being one of the most popular alternatives.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] Both methods can benefit from preconditioning, where gradient descent may require less assumptions on the preconditioner.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] Because each step is taken in the steepest direction, steepest-descent steps alternate between directions aligned with the extreme axes of the elongated level sets.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] When $\kappa (\mathbf {A} )$ is large, this produces a characteristic zig–zag path.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] The poor conditioning of $\mathbf {A}$ is the primary cause of the slow convergence, and orthogonality of successive residuals reinforces this alternation.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] As shown in the image on the right, steepest descent converges slowly due to the high condition number of $\mathbf {A}$ , and the orthogonality of residuals forces each new direction to undo the overshoot from the previous step.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] The result is a path that zigzags toward the solution.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] This inefficiency is one reason conjugate gradient or preconditioning methods are preferred.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] Gradient descent can also be used to solve a system of nonlinear equations.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] Below is an example that shows how to use the gradient descent to solve for three unknown variables, *x*1, *x*2, and *x*3.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] This example shows one iteration of the gradient descent.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] This can be done with any of a variety of line search algorithms.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] is a sizable decrease in the objective function.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] Further steps would reduce its value further until an approximate solution to the system was found.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] Gradient descent works in spaces of any number of dimensions, even in infinite-dimensional ones.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] In the latter case, the search space is typically a function space, and one calculates the Fréchet derivative of the functional to be minimized to determine the descent direction.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] That gradient descent works in any number of dimensions (finite number at least) can be seen as a consequence of the Cauchy–Schwarz inequality, i.e. the magnitude of the inner (dot) product of two vectors of any dimension is maximized when they are colinear.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] In the case of gradient descent, that would be when the vector of independent variable adjustments is proportional to the gradient vector of partial derivatives.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] The gradient descent can take many iterations to compute a local minimum with a required accuracy, if the curvature in different directions is very different for the given function.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] For such functions, preconditioning, which changes the geometry of the space to shape the function level sets like concentric circles, cures the slow convergence.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] Constructing and applying preconditioning can be computationally expensive, however.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] The gradient descent can be modified via momentums (Nesterov, Polyak, and Frank–Wolfe) and heavy-ball parameters (exponential moving averages and positive-negative momentum).
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] The main examples of such optimizers are Adam, DiffGrad, Yogi, AdaBelief, etc.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] Methods based on Newton's method and inversion of the Hessian using conjugate gradient techniques can be better alternatives.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] Generally, such methods converge in fewer iterations, but the cost of each iteration is higher.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] While it is sometimes possible to substitute gradient descent for a local search algorithm, gradient descent is not in the same family: although it is an iterative method for local optimization, it relies on an objective function's gradient rather than an explicit exploration of a solution space.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] Gradient descent can be viewed as applying Euler's method for solving ordinary differential equations $x'(t)=-\nabla f(x(t))$ to a gradient flow.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] In turn, this equation may be derived as an optimal controller for the control system $x'(t)=u(t)$ with $u(t)$ given in feedback form $u(t)=-\nabla f(x(t))$ .
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] Gradient descent can converge to a local minimum and slow down in a neighborhood of a saddle point.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] Even for unconstrained quadratic minimization, gradient descent develops a zig–zag pattern of subsequent iterates as iterations progress, resulting in slow convergence.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] Multiple modifications of gradient descent have been proposed to address these deficiencies.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] Yurii Nesterov has proposed a simple modification that enables faster convergence for convex problems and has been since further generalized.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] For unconstrained smooth problems, the method is called the fast gradient method (FGM) or the accelerated gradient method (AGM).
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] Specifically, if the differentiable function f is convex and $\nabla f$ is Lipschitz, and it is not assumed that f is strongly convex, then the error in the objective value generated at each step k by the gradient descent method will be bounded by ${\textstyle {\mathcal {O}}\left({k^{-1}}\right)}$ .
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] Using the Nesterov acceleration technique, the error decreases at ${\textstyle {\mathcal {O}}\left({k^{-2}}\right)}$ .
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] It is known that the rate ${\mathcal {O}}\left({k^{-2}}\right)$ for the decrease of the cost function is optimal for first-order optimization methods.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] Nevertheless, there is the opportunity to improve the algorithm by reducing the constant factor.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] The optimized gradient method (OGM) reduces that constant by a factor of two and is an optimal first-order method for large-scale problems.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] For constrained or non-smooth problems, Nesterov's FGM is called the fast proximal gradient method (FPGM), an acceleration of the proximal gradient method.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] Gradient descent with momentum remembers the solution update at each iteration, and determines the next update as a linear combination of the gradient and the previous update.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] For unconstrained quadratic minimization, a theoretical convergence rate bound of the heavy ball method is asymptotically the same as that for the optimal conjugate gradient method.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] This technique is used in stochastic gradient descent and as an extension to the backpropagation algorithms used to train artificial neural networks.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] In the direction of updating, stochastic gradient descent adds a stochastic property.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] The weights can be used to calculate the derivatives.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] Gradient descent can be extended to handle constraints by including a projection onto the set of constraints.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] This method is only feasible when the projection is efficiently computable on a computer.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] Under suitable assumptions, this method converges.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] This method is a specific case of the forward–backward algorithm for monotone inclusions (which includes convex programming and variational inequalities).
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] Gradient descent is a special case of mirror descent using the squared Euclidean distance as the given Bregman divergence.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] The properties of gradient descent depend on the properties of the objective function and the variant of gradient descent used (for example, if a line search step is used).
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] The assumptions made affect the convergence rate, and other properties, that can be proven for gradient descent.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] For example, if the objective is assumed to be strongly convex and lipschitz smooth, then gradient descent converges linearly with a fixed step size.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/gradient-descent] Looser assumptions lead to either weaker convergence guarantees or require a more sophisticated step size selection.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/learning-rate] In machine learning and statistics, the **learning rate** is a tuning parameter in an optimization algorithm that determines the step size at each iteration while moving toward a minimum of a loss function.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/learning-rate] Since it influences to what extent newly acquired information overrides old information, it metaphorically represents the speed at which a machine learning model "learns".
[src:gradient-descent-algo/learning-rate] In the adaptive control literature, the learning rate is commonly referred to as **gain**.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/learning-rate] In setting a learning rate, there is a trade-off between the rate of convergence and overshooting.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/learning-rate] While the descent direction is usually determined from the gradient of the loss function, the learning rate determines how big a step is taken in that direction.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/learning-rate] Too high a learning rate will make the learning jump over minima, but too low a learning rate will either take too long to converge or get stuck in an undesirable local minimum.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/learning-rate] In order to achieve faster convergence, prevent oscillations and getting stuck in undesirable local minima the learning rate is often varied during training either in accordance to a learning rate schedule or by using an adaptive learning rate.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/learning-rate] The learning rate and its adjustments may also differ per parameter, in which case it is a diagonal matrix that can be interpreted as an approximation to the inverse of the Hessian matrix in Newton's method.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/learning-rate] The learning rate is related to the step length determined by inexact line search in quasi-Newton methods and related optimization algorithms.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/learning-rate] Initial rate can be left as system default or can be selected using a range of techniques.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/learning-rate] A learning rate schedule changes the learning rate during learning and is most often changed between epochs/iterations.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/learning-rate] This is mainly done with two parameters: **decay** and **momentum**.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/learning-rate] There are many different learning rate schedules but the most common are **time-based, step-based** and **exponential**.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/learning-rate] where $\eta$ is the learning rate, $\eta _{0}$ is the original learning rate, d is a decay parameter and n is the iteration step.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/learning-rate] The *floor* function ( $\lfloor \dots \rfloor$ ) here drops the value of its input to 0 for all values smaller than 1.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/learning-rate] The issue with learning rate schedules is that they all depend on hyperparameters that must be manually chosen for each given learning session and may vary greatly depending on the problem at hand or the model used.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/learning-rate] To combat this, there are many different types of adaptive gradient descent algorithms such as Adagrad, Adadelta, RMSprop, and Adam which are generally built into deep learning libraries such as Keras.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/loss-function] In mathematical optimization and decision theory, a **loss function** or **cost function** (sometimes also called an error function) is a function that maps an event or values of one or more variables onto a real number intuitively representing some "cost" associated with the event.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/loss-function] An optimization problem seeks to minimize a loss function.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/loss-function] An **objective function** is either a loss function or its opposite (in specific domains, variously called a reward function, a profit function, a utility function, a fitness function, etc.), in which case it is to be maximized.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/loss-function] The loss function could include terms from several levels of the hierarchy.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/loss-function] In statistics, typically a loss function is used for parameter estimation, and the event in question is some function of the difference between estimated and true values for an instance of data.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/loss-function] The concept, as old as Laplace, was reintroduced in statistics by Abraham Wald in the middle of the 20th century.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/loss-function] In the context of economics, for example, this is usually economic cost or regret.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/loss-function] In classification, it is the penalty for an incorrect classification of an example.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/loss-function] In actuarial science, it is used in an insurance context to model benefits paid over premiums, particularly since the works of Harald Cramér in the 1920s.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/loss-function] In optimal control, the loss is the penalty for failing to achieve a desired value.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/loss-function] In financial risk management, the function is mapped to a monetary loss.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/loss-function] The use of a quadratic loss function is common, for example when using least squares techniques.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/loss-function] It is often more mathematically tractable than other loss functions because of the properties of variances, as well as being symmetric: an error above the target causes the same loss as the same magnitude of error below the target.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/loss-function] for some constant C ; the value of the constant makes no difference to a decision, and can be ignored by setting it equal to 1.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/loss-function] This is also known as the **squared error loss** (**SEL**).
[src:gradient-descent-algo/loss-function] Many common statistics, including t-tests, regression models, design of experiments, and much else, use least squares methods applied using linear regression theory, which is based on the quadratic loss function.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/loss-function] The quadratic loss function is also used in linear-quadratic optimal control problems.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/loss-function] In these problems, even in the absence of uncertainty, it may not be possible to achieve the desired values of all target variables.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/loss-function] Often loss is expressed as a quadratic form in the deviations of the variables of interest from their desired values; this approach is tractable because it results in linear first-order conditions.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/loss-function] In the context of stochastic control, the expected value of the quadratic form is used.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/loss-function] The quadratic loss assigns more importance to outliers than to the true data due to its square nature, so alternatives like the Huber, log-cosh and SMAE losses are used when the data has many large outliers.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/loss-function] In information theory, this loss function is known as Hamming distortion.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/loss-function] In many applications, objective functions, including loss functions as a particular case, are determined by the problem formulation.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/loss-function] In other situations, the decision maker’s preference must be elicited and represented by a scalar-valued function (called also utility function) in a form suitable for optimization — the problem that Ragnar Frisch has highlighted in his Nobel Prize lecture.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/loss-function] The existing methods for constructing objective functions are collected in the proceedings of two dedicated conferences.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/loss-function] In particular, Andranik Tangian showed that the most usable objective functions — quadratic and additive — are determined by a few indifference points.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/loss-function] He used this property in the models for constructing these objective functions from either ordinal or cardinal data that were elicited through computer-assisted interviews with decision makers.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/loss-function] Among other things, he constructed objective functions to optimally distribute budgets for 16 Westfalian universities and the European subsidies for equalizing unemployment rates among 271 German regions.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/loss-function] In some contexts, the value of the loss function itself is a random quantity because it depends on the outcome of a random variable X .
[src:gradient-descent-algo/loss-function] Both frequentist and Bayesian statistical theory involve making a decision based on the expected value of the loss function; however, this quantity is defined differently under the two paradigms.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/loss-function] We first define the expected loss in the frequentist context.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/loss-function] It is obtained by taking the expected value with respect to the probability distribution, $P_{\theta }$ , of the observed data, X .
[src:gradient-descent-algo/loss-function] This is also referred to as the **risk function** of the decision rule $\delta$ and the parameter $\theta$ .
[src:gradient-descent-algo/loss-function] Here the decision rule depends on the outcome of X .
[src:gradient-descent-algo/loss-function] where $M(\mathbf {x} )$ is known as the *predictive likelihood* wherein $\theta$ has been "integrated out," $\pi ^{*}(\theta |\mathbf {x} )$ is the posterior distribution, and the order of integration has been changed.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/loss-function] One then should choose the action $a^{*}$ which minimises this expected loss, which is referred to as *Bayes Risk*.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/loss-function] In the latter equation, the integrand inside $\mathrm {d} x$ is known as the *Posterior Risk*, and minimising it with respect to decision a also minimizes the overall Bayes Risk.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/loss-function] This optimal decision, $a^{*}$ is known as the *Bayes (decision) Rule* - it minimises the average loss over all possible states of nature $\theta$ , over all possible (probability-weighted) data outcomes.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/loss-function] One advantage of the Bayesian approach is to that one need only choose the optimal action under the actual observed data to obtain a uniformly optimal one, whereas choosing the actual frequentist optimal decision rule as a function of all possible observations, is a much more difficult problem.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/loss-function] Of equal importance though, the Bayes Rule reflects consideration of loss outcomes under different states of nature, $\theta$ .
[src:gradient-descent-algo/loss-function] In economics, decision-making under uncertainty is often modelled using the von Neumann–Morgenstern utility function of the uncertain variable of interest, such as end-of-period wealth.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/loss-function] Since the value of this variable is uncertain, so is the value of the utility function; it is the expected value of utility that is maximized.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/loss-function] A decision rule makes a choice using an optimality criterion.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/loss-function] Sound statistical practice requires selecting an estimator consistent with the actual acceptable variation experienced in the context of a particular applied problem.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/loss-function] Thus, in the applied use of loss functions, selecting which statistical method to use to model an applied problem depends on knowing the losses that will be experienced from being wrong under the problem's particular circumstances.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/loss-function] A common example involves estimating "location".
[src:gradient-descent-algo/loss-function] Still different estimators would be optimal under other, less common circumstances.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/loss-function] In economics, when an agent is risk neutral, the objective function is simply expressed as the expected value of a monetary quantity, such as profit, income, or end-of-period wealth.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/loss-function] For risk-averse or risk-loving agents, loss is measured as the negative of a utility function, and the objective function to be optimized is the expected value of utility.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/loss-function] Other measures of cost are possible, for example mortality or morbidity in the field of public health or safety engineering.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/loss-function] For most optimization algorithms, it is desirable to have a loss function that is globally continuous and differentiable.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/loss-function] Two very commonly used loss functions are the squared loss, $L(a)=a^{2}$ , and the absolute loss, $L(a)=|a|$ .
[src:gradient-descent-algo/loss-function] However the absolute loss has the disadvantage that it is not differentiable at $a=0$ .
[src:gradient-descent-algo/loss-function] The squared loss has the disadvantage that it has the tendency to be dominated by outliers—when summing over a set of a 's (as in ${\textstyle \sum _{i=1}^{n}L(a_{i})}$ ), the final sum tends to be the result of a few particularly large a -values, rather than an expression of the average a -value.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/loss-function] The choice of a loss function is not arbitrary.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/loss-function] It is very restrictive and sometimes the loss function may be characterized by its desirable properties.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/loss-function] Among the choice principles are, for example, the requirement of completeness of the class of symmetric statistics in the case of i.i.d. observations, the principle of complete information, and some others.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/loss-function] Edwards Deming and Nassim Nicholas Taleb argue that empirical reality, not nice mathematical properties, should be the sole basis for selecting loss functions, and real losses often are not mathematically nice and are not differentiable, continuous, symmetric, etc.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/loss-function] For example, a person who arrives before a plane gate closure can still make the plane, but a person who arrives after cannot, a discontinuity and asymmetry which makes arriving slightly late much more costly than arriving slightly early.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/loss-function] In drug dosing, the cost of too little drug may be lack of efficacy, while the cost of too much may be tolerable toxicity, another example of asymmetry.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/loss-function] Traffic, pipes, beams, ecologies, climates, etc. may tolerate increased load or stress with little noticeable change up to a point, then become backed up or break catastrophically.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/loss-function] These situations, Deming and Taleb argue, are common in real-life problems, perhaps more common than classical smooth, continuous, symmetric, differentials cases.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/stochastic-gradient-descent] The basic idea behind stochastic approximation can be traced back to the Robbins–Monro algorithm of the 1950s.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/stochastic-gradient-descent] Today, stochastic gradient descent has become an important optimization method in machine learning.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/stochastic-gradient-descent] Both statistical estimation and machine learning consider the problem of minimizing an objective function that has the form of a sum: $Q(w)={\frac {1}{n}}\sum _{i=1}^{n}Q_{i}(w),$ where the parameter w that minimizes $Q(w)$ is to be estimated.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/stochastic-gradient-descent] Each summand function $Q_{i}$ is typically associated with the i -th observation in the data set (used for training).
[src:gradient-descent-algo/stochastic-gradient-descent] In classical statistics, sum-minimization problems arise in least squares and in maximum-likelihood estimation (for independent observations).
[src:gradient-descent-algo/stochastic-gradient-descent] The general class of estimators that arise as minimizers of sums are called M-estimators.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/stochastic-gradient-descent] However, in statistics, it has been long recognized that requiring even local minimization is too restrictive for some problems of maximum-likelihood estimation.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/stochastic-gradient-descent] Therefore, contemporary statistical theorists often consider stationary points of the likelihood function (or zeros of its derivative, the score function, and other estimating equations).
[src:gradient-descent-algo/stochastic-gradient-descent] The sum-minimization problem also arises for empirical risk minimization.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/stochastic-gradient-descent] There, $Q_{i}(w)$ is the value of the loss function at i -th example, and $Q(w)$ is the empirical risk.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/stochastic-gradient-descent] In many cases, the summand functions have a simple form that enables inexpensive evaluations of the sum-function and the sum gradient.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/stochastic-gradient-descent] For example, in statistics, one-parameter exponential families allow economical function-evaluations and gradient-evaluations.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/stochastic-gradient-descent] However, in other cases, evaluating the sum-gradient may require expensive evaluations of the gradients from all summand functions.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/stochastic-gradient-descent] When the training set is enormous and no simple formulas exist, evaluating the sums of gradients becomes very expensive, because evaluating the gradient requires evaluating all the summand functions' gradients.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/stochastic-gradient-descent] To economize on the computational cost at every iteration, stochastic gradient descent samples a subset of summand functions at every step.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/stochastic-gradient-descent] This is very effective in the case of large-scale machine learning problems.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/stochastic-gradient-descent] In stochastic (or "on-line") gradient descent, the true gradient of $Q(w)$ is approximated by a gradient at a single sample: $w:=w-\eta \,\nabla Q_{i}(w).$ As the algorithm sweeps through the training set, it performs the above update for each training sample.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/stochastic-gradient-descent] Several passes can be made over the training set until the algorithm converges.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/stochastic-gradient-descent] If this is done, the data can be shuffled for each pass to prevent cycles.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/stochastic-gradient-descent] Typical implementations may use an adaptive learning rate so that the algorithm converges.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/stochastic-gradient-descent] A compromise between computing the true gradient and the gradient at a single sample is to compute the gradient against more than one training sample (called a "mini-batch") at each step.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/stochastic-gradient-descent] This can perform significantly better than "true" stochastic gradient descent described, because the code can make use of vectorization libraries rather than computing each step separately as was first shown in where it was called "the bunch-mode back-propagation algorithm".
[src:gradient-descent-algo/stochastic-gradient-descent] It may also result in smoother convergence, as the gradient computed at each step is averaged over more training samples.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/stochastic-gradient-descent] The convergence of stochastic gradient descent has been analyzed using the theories of convex minimization and of stochastic approximation.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/stochastic-gradient-descent] This is in fact a consequence of the Robbins–Siegmund theorem.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/stochastic-gradient-descent] This is the key difference between stochastic gradient descent and batched gradient descent.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/stochastic-gradient-descent] In general, given a linear regression ${\hat {y}}=\sum _{k\in 1:m}w_{k}x_{k}$ problem, stochastic gradient descent behaves differently when $m<n$ (underparameterized) and $m\geq n$ (overparameterized).
[src:gradient-descent-algo/stochastic-gradient-descent] In the overparameterized case, stochastic gradient descent converges to $\arg \min _{w:w^{T}x_{k}=y_{k}\forall k\in 1:n}\|w-w_{0}\|$ .
[src:gradient-descent-algo/stochastic-gradient-descent] That is, SGD converges to the interpolation solution with minimum distance from the starting $w_{0}$ .
[src:gradient-descent-algo/stochastic-gradient-descent] This is true even when the learning rate remains constant.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/stochastic-gradient-descent] In the underparameterized case, SGD does not converge if learning rate remains constant.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/stochastic-gradient-descent] In 1951, Herbert Robbins and Sutton Monro introduced the earliest stochastic approximation methods, preceding stochastic gradient descent.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/stochastic-gradient-descent] Building on this work one year later, Jack Kiefer and Jacob Wolfowitz published an optimization algorithm very close to stochastic gradient descent, using central differences as an approximation of the gradient.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/stochastic-gradient-descent] Later in the 1950s, Frank Rosenblatt used SGD to optimize his perceptron model, demonstrating the first applicability of stochastic gradient descent to neural networks.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/stochastic-gradient-descent] Backpropagation was first described in 1986, with stochastic gradient descent being used to efficiently optimize parameters across neural networks with multiple hidden layers.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/stochastic-gradient-descent] Soon after, another improvement was developed: mini-batch gradient descent, where small batches of data are substituted for single samples.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/stochastic-gradient-descent] In 1997, the practical performance benefits from vectorization achievable with such small batches were first explored, paving the way for efficient optimization in machine learning.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/stochastic-gradient-descent] As of 2023, this mini-batch approach remains the norm for training neural networks, balancing the benefits of stochastic gradient descent with gradient descent.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/stochastic-gradient-descent] By the 1980s, momentum had already been introduced, and was added to SGD optimization techniques in 1986.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/stochastic-gradient-descent] However, these optimization techniques assumed constant hyperparameters, i.e. a fixed learning rate and momentum parameter.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/stochastic-gradient-descent] In the 2010s, adaptive approaches to applying SGD with a per-parameter learning rate were introduced with AdaGrad (for "Adaptive Gradient") in 2011 and RMSprop (for "Root Mean Square Propagation") in 2012.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/stochastic-gradient-descent] In 2014, Adam (for "Adaptive Moment Estimation") was published, applying the adaptive approaches of RMSprop to momentum; many improvements and branches of Adam were then developed such as Adadelta, Adagrad, AdamW, and Adamax.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/stochastic-gradient-descent] Within machine learning, approaches to optimization in 2023 are dominated by Adam-derived optimizers, TensorFlow and PyTorch, by far the most popular machine learning libraries, as of 2023 largely only include Adam-derived optimizers, as well as predecessors to Adam such as RMSprop and classic SGD.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/stochastic-gradient-descent] PyTorch also partially supports limited-memory BFGS, a line-search method, but only for single-device setups without parameter groups.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/stochastic-gradient-descent] Stochastic gradient descent is a popular algorithm for training a wide range of models in machine learning, including (linear) support vector machines, logistic regression (see, e.g., Vowpal Wabbit) and graphical models.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/stochastic-gradient-descent] When combined with the backpropagation algorithm, it is the *de facto* standard algorithm for training artificial neural networks.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/stochastic-gradient-descent] Its use has been also reported in the Geophysics community, specifically to applications of Full Waveform Inversion (FWI).
[src:gradient-descent-algo/stochastic-gradient-descent] Stochastic gradient descent competes with the L-BFGS algorithm, which is also widely used.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/stochastic-gradient-descent] Stochastic gradient descent has been used since at least 1960 for training linear regression models, originally under the name ADALINE.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/stochastic-gradient-descent] Another stochastic gradient descent algorithm is the least mean squares (LMS) adaptive filter.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/stochastic-gradient-descent] Many improvements on the basic stochastic gradient descent algorithm have been proposed and used.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/stochastic-gradient-descent] In particular, in machine learning, the need to set a learning rate (step size) has been recognized as problematic.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/stochastic-gradient-descent] Setting this parameter too high can cause the algorithm to diverge; setting it too low makes it slow to converge.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/stochastic-gradient-descent] A conceptually simple extension of stochastic gradient descent makes the learning rate a decreasing function ηt of the iteration number t, giving a *learning rate schedule*, so that the first iterations cause large changes in the parameters, while the later ones do only fine-tuning.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/stochastic-gradient-descent] Such schedules have been known since the work of MacQueen on k-means clustering.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/stochastic-gradient-descent] Practical guidance on choosing the step size in several variants of SGD is given by Spall.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/stochastic-gradient-descent] As mentioned earlier, classical stochastic gradient descent is generally sensitive to learning rate η.
[src:gradient-descent-algo/stochastic-gradient-descent] Fast convergence requires large learning rates but this may induce numerical instability.
